p344
aS'Aldol_condensations are also commonly discussed in university level organic chemistry classes as a good bond-forming reaction that demonstrates important reaction mechanisms.'
p345
aS'In its usual form, it involves the nucleophilic addition of a ketone enolate to an aldehyde to form a b-hydroxy ketone, or "aldol" (aldehyde + alcohol), a structural unit found in many naturally occurring molecules and pharmaceuticals.The name aldol condensation is also commonly used, especially in biochemistry, to refer to just the first (addition) stage of the process--the aldol reaction itself--as catalyzed by aldolases.'
p346
aS'However, the aldol reaction is not formally a condensation reaction because it does not involve the loss of a small molecule.The reaction between an aldehyde/ketone and a carbonyl compound lacking an alpha-hydrogen (cross aldol condensation) is called the Claisen-Schmidt condensation.'
p347
aS'This reaction is named after two of its pioneering investigators Rainer_Ludwig_Claisen and J. G. Schmidt, who independently published on this topic in 1880 and 1881.'
p348
aS'An example is the synthesis of dibenzylideneacetone. Mechanism The first part of this reaction is an aldol reaction, the second part a dehydration--an elimination reaction(Involves removal of a water molecule or an alcohol molecule).'
p349
aS'Dehydration may be accompanied by decarboxylation when an activated carboxyl group is present.'
p350
aS'The aldol addition product can be dehydrated via two mechanisms; a strong base like potassium t-butoxide, potassium hydroxide or sodium hydride in an enolate mechanism, or in an acid-catalyzed enol mechanism.'
p351
aS'When dysregulated, aldosterone is pathogenic and contributes to the development and progression of cardiovascular and renal disease.'
p352
aS'Aldosterone has exactly the opposite function of the atrial natriuretic hormone secreted by the heart.Aldosterone is part of the renin-angiotensin system.'
p353
aS'Drugs that interfere with the secretion or action of aldosterone are in use as antihypertensives, like lisinopril, which lowers blood pressure by blocking the angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE), leading to lower aldosterone secretion.'
p354
aS'The net effect of these drugs is to reduce sodium and water retention but increase retention of potassium.'
p355
aS'Another example is spironolactone, a potassium-sparing diuretic, which decreases blood pressure by releasing fluid from the body while retaining potassium.'
p356
aS'It was first isolated by Simpson and Tait in 1953. Synthesis The corticosteroids are synthesized from cholesterol within the zona glomerulosa of adrenal cortex.'
p357
aS'Most steroidogenic reactions are catalysed by enzymes of the cytochrome P450 family.'
