aS'Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.To be cost-effective and to enable efficient use of data, caches are relatively small.'
p1542
aS'Nevertheless, caches have proven themselves in many areas of computing because access patterns in typical computer applications exhibit the locality of reference.'
p1543
aS'Moreover, access patterns exhibit temporal locality if data is requested again that has been recently requested already, while spatial locality refers to requests for data physically stored close to data that has been already requested. Operation Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.'
p1544
aS'Central processing units (CPUs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently use a cache, as do web browsers and web servers.A cache is made up of a pool of entries.'
p1545
aS'Each entry has associated data, which is a copy of the same data in some backing store.'
p1546
aS'Each entry also has a tag, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.'
p1547
aS'If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.'
p1548
