aS'The term chirality is derived from the Greek word for hand, kheir (kheir).'
p1934
aS'It is a mathematical approach to the concept of "handedness".Conversely, an achiral object, such as an atom, is symmetric; its mirror image is not truly opposite, but rather is indistinguishable from the original.In chemistry, chirality usually refers to molecules.'
p1935
aS'Two mirror images of a chiral molecule are called enantiomers or optical isomers.'
p1936
aS'Pairs of enantiomers are often designated as "right-" and "left-handed".Molecular chirality is of interest because of its application to stereochemistry in inorganic chemistry, organic chemistry, physical chemistry, biochemistry, and supramolecular chemistry. History The term optical activity is derived from the interaction of chiral materials with polarized light.'
p1937
aS'In a solution, the (-)-form, or levorotary form, of an optical isomer rotates the plane of a beam of linearly polarized light counterclockwise.'
p1938
aS'The (+)-form, or dextrorotatory form, of an optical isomer does the opposite.'
