aS'In the preface to the first edition Kant explains what he means by a critique of pure reason: "I do not mean by this a critique of books and systems, but of the faculty of reason in general, in respect of all knowledge after which it may strive independently of all experience.'
p2298
aS'"Before Kant, it was generally held that truths of reason must be analytic, meaning that what is stated in the predicate must already be present in the subject (for example, "An intelligent man is intelligent" or "An intelligent man is a man").'
p2299
aS'In either case, the judgment is analytic because it is ascertained by analyzing the subject.'
p2300
aS'It was thought that all truths of reason, or necessary truths, are of this kind: that in all of them there is a predicate that is only part of the subject of which it is asserted.'
p2301
aS'If this were so, attempting to deny anything that could be known a priori (for example, "An intelligent man is not intelligent" or "An intelligent man is not a man") would involve a contradiction.'
p2302
aS"It was therefore thought that the law of contradiction is sufficient to establish all a priori knowledge. Kant's rejection of Hume's empiricism Before Kant (1724-1804), David Hume (1711-1776) accepted the general view of rationalism about a priori knowledge."
p2303
aS'However, upon closer examination of the subject, Hume discovered that some judgments thought to be analytic, especially those related to cause and effect, were actually synthetic (i.e., no analysis of the subject will reveal the predicate).'
