p3056
aS'Today, particles that obey the exclusion principle are called "fermions".'
p3057
aS'Later Pauli postulated the existence of an uncharged invisible particle emitted along with an electron during beta decay, to satisfy the law of conservation of energy.'
p3058
aS'Fermi took up this idea, developing a model that incorporated the postulated particle, which he named the "neutrino".'
p3059
aS"His theory, later referred to as Fermi's interaction and still later as weak interaction, described one of the four fundamental forces of nature."
p3060
aS'The same situation exists in classical mechanics: only a change or difference in energy carries physical meaning.'
p3061
aS'Enthalpy itself is a thermodynamic potential, so in order to measure the enthalpy of a system, we must refer to a defined reference point; therefore what we measure is the change in enthalpy, DH.'
p3062
aS'The change DH is positive in endothermic reactions, and negative in heat-releasing exothermic processes.For processes under constant pressure, DH is equal to the change in the internal energy of the system, plus the pressure-volume work that the system has done on its surroundings.'
p3063
aS'This means that the change in enthalpy under such conditions is the heat absorbed (or released) by the material through a chemical reaction or by external heat transfer.'
p3064
aS'Enthalpies for chemical substances at constant pressure assume standard state: most commonly 1 bar pressure.'
p3065
aS'Standard state does not, strictly speaking, specify a temperature (see standard state), but expressions for enthalpy generally reference the standard heat of formation at 25 degC.Enthalpy of ideal gases and incompressible solids and liquids does not depend on pressure, unlike entropy and Gibbs energy.'
p3066
aS'Real materials at common temperatures and pressures usually closely approximate this behavior, which greatly simplifies enthalpy calculation and use in practical designs and analyses. Origins The word enthalpy is based on the Greek enthalpein (enthalpein), which means "to warm in".'
p3067
aS'Systems that are not isolated may decrease in entropy, provided they increase the entropy of their environment by at least that same amount.'
p3068
aS'Since entropy is a state function, the change in the entropy of a system is the same for any process that goes from a given initial state to a given final state, whether the process is reversible or irreversible.'
p3069
aS'However, irreversible processes increase the combined entropy of the system and its environment.The change in entropy (DS) of a system was originally defined for a thermodynamically reversible process as,where T is the absolute temperature of the system, dividing an incremental reversible transfer of heat into that system (dQ).'
p3070
aS'(If heat is transferred out the sign would be reversed giving a decrease in entropy of the system.)'
p3071
aS'The above definition is sometimes called the macroscopic definition of entropy because it can be used without regard to any microscopic description of the contents of a system.'
p3072
aS'The concept of entropy has been found to be generally useful and has several other formulations.'
p3073
aS'Entropy was discovered when it was noticed to be a quantity that behaves as a function of state, as a consequence of the second law of thermodynamics.Entropy is an extensive property.'
