aS'Neurons can connect to each other to form neural networks.'
p6934
aS'Neurons are the core components of the brain and spinal cord of the central nervous system (CNS), and of the ganglia of the peripheral nervous system (PNS).'
p6935
aS'Specialized types of neurons include: sensory neurons which respond to touch, sound, light and all other stimuli affecting the cells of the sensory organs that then send signals to the spinal cord and brain, motor neurons that receive signals from the brain and spinal cord to cause muscle contractions and affect glandular outputs, and interneurons which connect neurons to other neurons within the same region of the brain, or spinal cord in neural networks.A typical neuron consists of a cell body (soma), dendrites, and an axon.'
p6936
aS'The term neurite is used to describe either a dendrite or an axon, particularly in its undifferentiated stage.'
p6937
aS'Dendrites are thin structures that arise from the cell body, often extending for hundreds of micrometres and branching multiple times, giving rise to a complex "dendritic tree".'
p6938
aS'An axon is a special cellular extension that arises from the cell body at a site called the axon hillock and travels for a distance, as far as 1 meter in humans or even more in other species.'
p6939
aS'The cell body of a neuron frequently gives rise to multiple dendrites, but never to more than one axon, although the axon may branch hundreds of times before it terminates.'
p6940
aS'Neutron_stars are very hot and are supported against further collapse by quantum degeneracy pressure due to the phenomenon described by the Pauli_exclusion_principle, which states that no two neutrons (or any other fermionic particles) can occupy the same place and quantum state simultaneously.A neutron star has a mass of at least 1.1 and perhaps up to 3 solar masses (M), though the highest observed mass is 2.01 M Neutron_stars typically have a surface temperature around ~70056000000000000006x105 K. Neutron_stars have overall densities of 70173700000000000003.7x1017 to 70175900000000000005.9x1017 kg/m3 (70142600000000000002.6x1014 to 70144099999999999994.1x1014 times the density of the Sun), which is comparable to the approximate density of an atomic nucleus of 70173000000000000003x1017 kg/m3.'
p6941
aS"The neutron star's density varies from below 70091000000000000001x109 kg/m3 in the crust--increasing with depth--to above 70176000000000000006x1017 or 70178000000000000008x1017 kg/m3 deeper inside (denser than an atomic nucleus)."
p6942
aS'A normal-sized matchbox containing neutron-star material would have a mass of approximately 5 trillion tons or ~1000 km3 of Earth rock.In general, compact stars of less than 1.39 M (the Chandrasekhar_limit) are white dwarfs, whereas compact stars with a mass between that and 3 M (the Tolman-Oppenheimer-Volkoff limit) should be neutron stars.'
p6943
aS'The maximum observed mass of neutron stars is about 2 M. Compact stars with more than 10 M will overcome the neutron degeneracy pressure and gravitational collapse will usually occur to produce a black hole.'
p6944
aS'The smallest observed mass of a black hole is about 5 M. Between these, hypothetical intermediate-mass stars such as quark stars and electroweak stars have been proposed, but none have been shown to exist.'
p6945
aS'The equations of state of matter at such high densities are not precisely known because of the theoretical and empirical difficulties.Some neutron stars rotate very rapidly (up to 716 times a second, or approximately 43,000 revolutions per minute) and emit beams of electromagnetic radiation as pulsars.'
p6946
aS'Indeed, the discovery of pulsars in 1967 first suggested that neutron stars exist.'
p6947
aS"The name came from papo (to unite) and ua (negation), which means not united or, territory that geographically is far away (and thus not united).Ploeg reports that the word papua is often said to derive from the Malay word papua or pua-pua, meaning 'frizzly-haired', referring to the highly curly hair of the inhabitants of these areas."
p6948
aS"Another possibility, (put forward by Sollewijn Gelpke in 1993) is that it comes from the Biak phrase sup i papwa which means 'the land below [the sunset]' and refers to the islands west of the Bird's Head, as far as Halmahera."
p6949
aS'Whatever the origin of the name Papua, it came to be associated with this area, and more especially with Halmahera, which was known to the Portuguese by this name during the era of their colonization in this part of the world.When the Portuguese and Spanish explorers arrived in the island via the Spice Islands, they also referred to the island as Papua.'
