aS"The transition between the inner core and outer core is located approximately 5,150 km (3,200 mi) beneath the Earth's surface. Properties The temperature of the outer core ranges from 4,300 K (4,030 degC; 7,280 degF) in the outer regions to 6,000 K (5,730 degC; 10,340 degF) near the inner core."
p7354
aS'Because of its high temperature, modeling work has shown that the outer core is a low viscosity fluid (about ten times the viscosity of liquid metals at the surface) that convects turbulently.'
p7355
aS"Eddy currents in the nickel iron fluid of the outer core are believed to influence the Earth's magnetic field."
p7356
aS"The average magnetic field strength in the Earth's outer core was measured to be 2.5 millitesla, 50 times stronger than the magnetic field at the surface."
p7357
aS'The outer core is not under enough pressure to be solid, so it is liquid even though it has a composition similar to that of the inner core.'
p7358
aS'Sulfur and oxygen could also be present in the outer core.As heat is transferred outward toward the mantle, the net trend is for the inner boundary of the liquid region to freeze, causing the solid inner core to grow.'
p7359
aS"This growth rate is estimated to be 1 mm per year. Effect on life Convection of liquid metals in the outer core creates the Earth's magnetic field, and without this, life would be significantly different then what we have today. See also Structure of the Earth References  External links Outer_core from universetoday.com"
