aS"The word prion, coined in 1982 by Stanley B. Prusiner, is derived from the words protein and infection, in reference to a prion's ability to self-propagate and transmit its conformation to other prions."
p7956
aS'While several yeast proteins have been identified as having prionogenic properties, the first prion protein was discovered in mammals and is referred to as the major prion protein (PrP).'
p7957
aS'This infectious agent causes mammalian transmissible spongiform encephalopathies, including bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE, also known as "mad cow disease") and scrapie in sheep.'
p7958
aS'In humans, PrP causes Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD), variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (vCJD), Gerstmann-Straussler-Scheinker syndrome, Fatal Familial Insomnia and kuru.A protein as an infectious agent stands in contrast to all other known infectious agents, like viruses, bacteria, fungi, or parasites--all of which must contain nucleic acids (either DNA, RNA, or both).'
p7959
aS'All known prion diseases in mammals affect the structure of the brain or other neural tissue and all are currently untreatable and universally fatal.While PrP is considered the only mammalian prion, prion-like domains have been found in a variety of other mammalian proteins.'
