aS'A reagent, called the titrant or titrator is prepared as a standard solution.'
p10261
aS'A known concentration and volume of titrant reacts with a solution of analyte or titrand to determine concentration.'
p10262
aS'The volume of titrant reacted is called titration volume. History and etymology The word "titration" comes from the Latin word titulus, meaning inscription or title.'
p10263
aS'The French word titre, also from this origin, means rank.Volumetric analysis originated in late 18th-century France.'
p10264
aS'Francois-Antoine-Henri Descroizilles (fr) developed the first burette (which was similar to a graduated cylinder) in 1791.'
p10265
aS'Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac developed an improved version of the burette that included a side arm, and coined the terms "pipette" and "burette" in an 1824 paper on the standardization of indigo solutions.'
p10266
aS'A major breakthrough in the methodology and popularization of volumetric analysis was due to Karl Friedrich Mohr, who redesigned the burette by placing a clamp and a tip at the bottom, and wrote the first textbook on the topic, Lehrbuch der chemisch-analytischen Titrirmethode (Textbook of analytical-chemical titration methods), published in 1855. Procedure A typical titration begins with a beaker or Erlenmeyer flask containing a very precise volume of the analyte and a small amount of indicator (such as phenolphthalein) placed underneath a calibrated burette or chemistry pipetting syringe containing the titrant.'
